pull_request.title: [Issue #49] User Story 2.3: GitHub MCP Server — github_get_issue (Template-Conformant)
pull_request.body:
- Implement in-process github MCP provider
- Expose github_get_issue tool constrained to GitHub.com
- Add token authentication with proper redaction
- Classify API errors (401/403 → fatal, 429 → retryable)
- Add unit and e2e tests
- Add static error definitions for GitHub provider to fix golangci-lint err113 violations
- Move environment variable resolution to shared ResolveEnvVar function in types package
- Update GitHub provider to use wrapped static errors instead of dynamic errors
- Add environment variable resolution to MCP server configuration
- Update GitHub provider tests to match new error message format
- Improve GitHub integration test to verify actual tool execution flow

**Related Issue**: #49: GitHub Reader Step Implementation

Implements GitHub MCP provider exposing github_get_issue tool with proper error handling, linting compliance, and comprehensive testing. The provider includes token authentication, error classification, and environment variable resolution for secure configuration management.

## Acceptance Criteria

[✓] Provider registers github_get_issue tool
[✓] Only api.github.com domain accepted
[✓] Success: Returns { title, body, state, labels } in Result and ContextWrites
[✓] Errors: Classified and written to ContextWrites.last_error
[✓] Tokens redacted from logs
[✓] Unit tests pass
[✓] All linting issues resolved with static error definitions
[✓] Environment variable resolution implemented
[ ] E2E tests pass with real GitHub API (requires .env.e2e with GITHUB_TOKEN)

## Implementation Details

- Created internal/github/provider.go with GitHub REST v3 client
- Added comprehensive parameter validation and error classification
- Implemented custom token transport for authentication
- Registered provider in MCP registry
- Added static error definitions to resolve golangci-lint violations
- Moved environment variable resolution to shared types package
- Added unit tests covering all validation scenarios
- Added e2e test framework (passes tool discovery, execution requires credentials)

  * Centralized environment-variable resolution into a shared ResolveEnvVar utility.

issue.body:
> Forked from #6.  

We need to provide clean error messages before we get to spawning binaries.  For example, in #6 we need to cleanly indicate the problem is spaces in the package id cannot include whitespace.  From the [nuspec docs](https://docs.nuget.org/create/nuspec-reference) the package id is: 

> The unique identifier for the package. This is the package name that is shown when packages are listed using the Package Manager Console. These are also used when installing a package using the Install-Package command within the Package Manager Console. Package IDs may not contain any spaces or characters that are invalid in an URL. In general, they follow the same rules as .NET namespaces do. So Foo.Bar is a valid ID, Foo! and Foo Bar are not.

As well, we should make the [app model](https://github.com/mongodb-js/electron-app-model) should make the default conform to the spec.

comment.body:
Yeah, users with problems rarely want to hear about nuance or context. :-/ Some of that is a problem that no amount of the best writing will ever solve.

I think we've already done a good job of that in [the revised intro](https://ytdl-sub.readthedocs.io/en/latest/introduction.html#what-is-ytdl-sub) and then elaborated on in [the revised Motivation section](https://ytdl-sub.readthedocs.io/en/latest/introduction.html#motivation). Part of the reason I put as much love into describing the relationship to ``yt-dlp`` is because that's one of the things I learned a lot about while getting up to speed with ``ytdl-sub`` and that I wished had been explained to me explicitly earlier.

That said, I have *not* needed to learn much about ``yt-dlp`` beyond what's now included there to get use out of this project. The extent of my interaction with ``yt-dlp`` has been copying and pasting stuff under ``ytdl_options:`` by rote and that's served me well. I haven't even opened their docs that I recall.

So I can't think of anything more to say about ``yt-dlp`` or anything else I wished I'd known more about it. I think adding more to those intro sections makes those docs less focused and effective and I think calling it required knowledge is not very true. If I had more to say about it, I'd probably place it in [the plugin refs](https://ytdl-sub.readthedocs.io/en/latest/config_reference/plugins.html#ytdl-options).

That said, I *do* come in with significant technical experience if not domain experience, so there may well be things that need explaining for a significant portion of the user base that I just can't see. What else beyond the intro sections do you think might be said about the relationship that might help users better understand?

issue.body:
Bumps [react-pdf](https://github.com/wojtekmaj/react-pdf/tree/HEAD/packages/react-pdf) from 9.2.1 to 10.1.0.
Release notes

Sourced from react-pdf's releases.

v10.1.0

What's new?

  • Added support for functions as children. React-PDF has never been simpler to work with! Say goodbye toonLoadSuccess, say goodbye to setting number of pages in your own state, say goodbye to extra renders! Now, rendering a simple document is as trivial as: 
    <Document file="sample.pdf">
  {({ pdf }) => Array(pdf.numPages)
    .fill(null)
    .map((_, index) => <Page key={index} pageIndex={index} />
  ))}
</Document>
    Thanks @​adamaoc for inspiration!
  • Updated PDF.js to 5.3.93.
  • Updated documentation on JPEG 2000 support.
  • Updated dependencies.
  • Exported LinkService type for convenience.

What's changed?

  • usePageContext will now provide non-null value sooner than before, before the page is actually loaded. This is uniform with how useDocumentContext behaves and with how types were designed from the start, so you should not be affected by this change.
  • React-PDF now targets es2018 and not es2017. PDF.js, our core dependency, already used modern JavaScript syntax, so you should not be affected by this change.

v10.0.1

Bug fixes

  • Fixed commonly used types not reexported.

v10.0.0

See Upgrade guide from version 9.x to 10.x.

After more than a year since our last major release, we're thrilled to bring you React-PDF 10.

This update includes a major PDF.js upgrade, new features to make your life easier, improved stability, and some important breaking changes.

👀 Want to see exciting features more often? Consider sponsoring React-PDF.

❗️ = breaking change

What's new?

  • ❗️ Dropped CommonJS build, making the package ESM-only. Chances are you're not going to be affected by this change at all, as all common bundlers support ESM out of the box.
    • However, you may encounter issues running unit tests using Jest. Consider migrating to Vitest.
  • Updated PDF.js to 5.3.31.
    • Performance boosts: Key rendering routines refactored to cut memory usage and speed up page loading.
    • JPEG2000 downscaling: Automatic downscale of large JPEG2000 images during decoding to improve render times.
    • CMYK JPEG fix: Correct handling of the alpha channel when WebAssembly is disabled.
    • Viewer stability: Better handling of missing/invalid Content-Range headers.
    • API cleanup: Removed deprecated options, adopted parameter objects for core methods, and introduced private class fields for cleaner code.
  • Added support for scale prop in Document component, allowing you to set the scale for the entire document.

... (truncated)

issue.title: Advice on collectstatic in build stage
issue.body:
So I'd be glad to have your help here with an issue but maybe also something to reconsider for this project.

Basically I'm deploying to Railway which injects ENV vars in the build stage of the Dockerfile only if they're specified as `ARG`.

I have an app that requires ENV vars that shouldn't have a default value (for example: fail loudly if we don't have `EMAIL_TOKEN`). Those are defined in my settings module.

You can see where I'm going with this. If I want to use this template on Railway I have two choices:

1. Move `collectstatic` out of the Dockerfile (will this have negative consequences? What do I do in development mode?)

2. Always define defaults for ENV vars. Passing each required ENV var as ARG to Dockerfile is not realistic, there are too many. Even if I was willing to pass secrets as ARGs (and I'm not)

Can collectstatic be moved out of Dockerfile somehow, without negative consequences?

comment.body:
> Another thing I'm considering is just moving this block out of build time and to runtime (since I'm already doing this in Railway anyway).

Just to close the loop on this, this is what I ended up doing. My project is quite complex, old (8 years old), and I wouldn't like to introduce conditional logic for my environment variables. I'm using healthchecks to verify the new deployments have finished doing maintenance (`migrate` and `collectstatic`) where possible. Thanks for all the help @nickjj!
